 &=x\log^2 x - 2x\log x +2x+C

Solution 2: Our integrand is two functions multiplied together: \log x and \log x. So, we will use integration by parts with u=\log x, \dee{v}=\log x, \dee{u}=\frac{1}{x}\dee{x}, and (using the antiderivative of logarithm, found in Example in the text) v=x\log x -x.


\int \log^2 x \dee{x}&=(\underbrace{\log x}_u) (\underbrace{x\log x - x}_{v})
